t of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunigan","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish or Irish   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Conahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac.","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Connachaín</b> (see   Cunningham  )."]},{"name":"Conaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Fergal.","Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire) Irish (Donegal): from <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b>, see   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cuningham","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cummingham","meanings":["(1997: 117;2007: 199; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cunnigham","meanings":["(2007: 429; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish (Donegal): variant of   Cunningham  ."]}]},{"name":"Earl","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>e(o)rl</i> ‘earl’, a traditional English title of nobility equivalent in rank to French and Norman   Count  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earle","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Harle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Johann, Kurt.","South German (<b>Härle</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>hār</i> ‘hair’.","English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Kirkharle and Little Harle in Northumberland (earlier simply <i>Herle</i>, <i>Harle</i>), possibly named from an Old English personal name <i>Herela</i> (a derivative of various compound names with the first element <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’."]},{"name":"Earls","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with genitival <i>-s</i>, denoting someone who was a member of an earl's household, or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland, when this is not the English name, it is from Gaelic <b>Mac an Iarla</b> ‘son of the earl’."]},{"name":"Hearl","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Count","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Earll","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Earl  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alexander Cunningham, Earl of Glencairn was born in 1510. He had at least 1 daughter with Janet “Jean” Hamilton. He died on 23 November 1574, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1510–23 November 1574":"1510–23. november 1574","1517–1574":"1517–1574","1533–1573":"1533–1573","1510–1574":"1510–1574","23 November 1574":"23. november 1574","1533":"1533","1510":"1510","1574":"1574","1573":"1573","1517":"1517","20 July 1573":"20. juuli 1573","Kilmarnock, Stirling, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland","Glengarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Glengarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1510–23 November 1574":"1510–23. marraskuuta 1574","1517–1574":"1517–1574","1533–1573":"1533–1573","1510–1574":"1510–1574","23 November 1574":"23. marraskuuta 1574","1533":"1533","1510":"1510","1574":"1574","1573":"1573","1517":"1517","20 July 1573":"20. heinäkuuta 1573","Kilmarnock, Stirling, Scotland":"Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland","Glengarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Glengarnock, Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1510–23 November 1574":"1510–23 novembre 1574","1517–1574":"1517–1574","1533–1573":"1533–1573","1510–1574":"1510–1574","23 November 1574":"23 novembre 1574","1533":"1533","1510":"1510","1574":"1574","1573":"1573","1517":"1517","20 July 1573":"20 juillet 1573","Kilmarnock, Stirling, Scotland":"Craigie, Ay